<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate heat loss for a house?", answer: "For each part of the building envelope, compute Q = U × A × ΔT. U is 1 divided by the R-value, A is the area, and ΔT is the difference between your indoor design temperature and the coldest outdoor temperature of the year. Add the numbers for walls, roof, windows, and floor, plus a term for air infiltration, and you get the whole-house heat loss in BTU/hr." },
  { question: "What is a design temperature?", answer: "The design temperature is a statistical extreme — typically the 99% winter heating design temperature, meaning only 1% of hours per year are colder. For example, Minneapolis has a winter design temp of −11 °F; Dallas is 22 °F; Miami is 44 °F. Look up your local design temps from ASHRAE or a climate data service." },
  { question: "How big a furnace do I need?", answer: "Size the furnace to your design heat loss. A well-insulated 2,000 sq ft house in a cold climate typically loses 40,000-60,000 BTU/hr at design conditions. An older house with poor insulation may lose 80,000-100,000 BTU/hr. Oversizing by more than 20% causes short-cycling and reduced efficiency, so match the output closely to the calculated load." },
  { question: "What is the difference between heat loss and Manual J?", answer: "ACCA Manual J is a detailed room-by-room heat loss and gain calculation that accounts for orientation, shading, air tightness, and many other factors. It is required for HVAC contractors by code in many jurisdictions. This calculator is a 'Manual J lite' that gives a whole-house estimate suitable for planning and budgeting — not a substitute for a full Manual J when sizing equipment professionally." },
  { question: "How much does air infiltration matter?", answer: "In an average house, infiltration is 20-40% of total heat loss. A leaky 1960s house at 1.0 ACH loses far more through air leaks than through the walls. A modern tight house at 0.25 ACH may lose only 10% of its total to infiltration. A blower door test gives the actual number; 0.5 ACH is a reasonable average for a typical existing home." }
]) %>

